<subSubSection id="4FF0F1E8FF0CFF46A7ADFD29FD9DDF9F" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="0755A263FF0CFF46A7ADFD29FEB8DEE1" blockId="149.[189,382,710,736]" box="[189,382,710,736]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
<heading id="5C1D150FFF0CFF46A7ADFD29FEB8DEE1" bold="true" box="[189,382,710,736]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" reason="3">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF0CFF46A7ADFD29FEB8DEE1" bold="true" box="[189,382,710,736]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Natural history</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0755A263FF0CFF46A7ADFD1AFD9DDF9F" blockId="149.[188,1399,757,926]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">
The 
<typeStatus id="D8511CC1FF0CFF46A7E1FD1AFE9EDF0E" box="[241,344,757,783]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected under a rock in a small rocky outcrop near a dry creek-bed, in closed-canopy primary rainforest. The female possessed a brood sac and carried 
<specimenCount id="11EC69EAFF0CFF46A4D4FCF6FB8EDF32" box="[964,1096,793,819]" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" type="egg">seven eggs</specimenCount>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="637BDF92FF0CFF46A344FCF6FB3EDF32" author="Harms D." box="[1108,1272,793,819]" firstAuthor="Harms" journalOrPublisher="Evolutionary Systematics" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" pagination="45 - 53" part="2" refId="ref149325" refString="Harms D. 2018. A new species of Charinus (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from Ghana, with notes on West African whip spiders. Evolutionary Systematics 2: 45 - 53. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / evolsyst. 2.24505" title="A new species of Charinus (Amblypygi: Charinidae) from Ghana, with notes on West African whip spiders" type="journal article" year="2018">Harms (2018)</bibRefCitation>
noted that this was the smallest whip spider in western Africa and might have a preference for rocky boulders in densely vegetated areas, under which it retreats. 
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF0CFF46A5EAFC8FFCA0DF7B" authorityName="Thorel" authorityYear="1876" box="[762,870,864,890]" class="Arachnida" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ricinulei" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Ricinulei</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="C0EAD9E0FF0CFF46A466FC8FFBDDDF7B" box="[886,1051,864,890]" class="Arachnida" family="Ricinoididae" genus="Ricinoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ricinulei" pageId="149" pageNumber="150" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="359E7E71FF0CFF46A466FC8FFC34DF7B" box="[886,1010,864,890]" italics="true" pageId="149" pageNumber="150">Ricinoides</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
) and unidentified schizomids were observed at the same outcrop.
</paragraph>
